                     <origDate notBefore="1733" notAfter="1755">1733-1755 (?). In the supplication
                        formula of <locus target="#2ra">2ra</locus> (incipit page of Text I-1) and
                           <locus target="#5rb">5rb</locus> are mentioned ʾIyasu as king, Walatta
                        Giyorgis as queen, and Walda Lǝʿul as ras. On <locus target="#109rb">109rb</locus>, is mentioned only King ʾIyasu together with Queen Walatta
                        Giyorgis. &#xD; ʾIyasu II was King of Ethiopia in 1730-55 (cp. EAE III,
                        251-52); Walatta Giyorgis is the baptismal name of Bǝrhān Mogasā (known as
                        Mǝntǝwwāb; cp. EAE I, 534-35 and also EAE III, 251-52), mother of ʾIyāsu II,
                        who ruled with him. &#xD; Ras Walda Lǝʿul (d. 1767; about him cp. EAE IV,
                        1104) was the brother of Walatta Giyorgis. He received the title of rās in
                        1733.&#xD; Quires XXII-XXIX are probably of a later time.</origDate>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>Gabra Masqal is mentioned in most of the
                     supplication formulas of the text (e.g., <locus target="#8rb">8rb</locus>, 8va,
                     17ra, 67vb), usually with "his lady and beloved" (ʾǝgzǝʾtu wa-fǝqǝrtu) Walatta
                     Qǝddusan.&#xD; On <locus target="#2ra">2ra</locus> and 5rb, her name occurs
                     together with those of King ʾIyasu, Queen Walatta Giyorgis and <roleName type="title">rās</roleName> Walda Lǝʿul, all of them mentioned as her
                     children; later in the text she is mentioned, more specifically, as the mother
                     of Queen Walatta Giyorgis (esp. <locus target="#156ra">156ra</locus>, 165vab)
                     and of <roleName type="title">rās</roleName> Walda Lǝʿul (esp. <locus target="#156rb">156rb</locus>).</provenance>
